      %h2 What makes Ruby, Ruby?
      %p Throughout two decades and over 100 releases, the Ruby language has evolved and grown around simple ideas and elegant constructs whose principles have changed surprisingly little.

      %p But, a deeper study of Ruby's history and codebase will uncover some curious detours and dead ends: syntax and features which were either revised or abandoned. An examination of these changes and, the reasons behind them, can serve both to entertain and inform. In this talk we'll visit some of Ruby's features, what remains in Ruby and what was left out and, in the process, gain a unique insight into what makes today's Ruby, Ruby.

      %p These are some of the Ruby concepts that will be presented in this talk:

      %ol
        %li Constants and their lookup
        %li Variable scope, self and bindings
        %li Method parameters and super
        %li Callable objects

      %p Each topic will be introduced with easy to follow code examples. Once described, we will investigate their availability across 20 years of Ruby versions, eventually trying to elucidate the motivations for these changes. The talk will target Rubyists of all skill levels.

    .bio
      %h2 Bio
      %p Adrián got his start programming in C and Perl in the early days of the Web, but has been working primarily with Ruby since 2005. He has been quietly influencing the Web in Argentina for the better part of the past 18 years: he implemented the first search engines for Clarín and La Nación, and was the former Technical Director of Yahoo Argentina since its launch. Adrián is now a Ruby developer at WyeWorks.

      %p A lifelong technology enthusiast with a background in mechanical engineering, Adrián is just as comfortable coding Ruby and JavaScript as he is hacking motorcycle engines or tuning the perfect snowboarding setup.

