      %h2 Derailing Irrationality
      %p Cognitive biases enable faster decisions when timeliness is more valuable than accuracy. They are very hard to detect and rarely discussed. Without realizing it we ask survey questions of our customers and clients that yield biased answers, which in turn lead to features that are not useful. We review code in ways that cause frustration, and hurt feelings. We take on technical debt because of invisible and nearly imperceptible forces in our minds that cause us to make irrational decisions. This talk will help developers to understand how to think rationally in order to act quickly, write better software and be happier while doing it.

      %p In the presentation we will talk about the current moment bias, the fairness bias, impostor syndrome, the IKEA effect, the diagnosis bias, the principle of reactance and how these effects become formidable enemies on the way to creating cohesive teams and simple software. We will learn how to recognize when these biases take effect and how to overcome them.

      %p By the end of this talk people will know:
      %ol
        %li How to review code and have your code reviewed without hurting feelings and maintaining maximum collaboration.
        %li How to ask questions in such a way that we do not implement code that is not needed.
        %li How to recognize and become aware of the effects of biases in your life, and how to manage them.
        %li How to resist the cognitive biases that lead us to take on technical debt and build features people will not use.
        %li How common biases make you feel that you are powerless and less creative at work than you would like to be (and how to help yourself and others overcome these biases).
        %li Signs that a bias is causing you to act irrationally.

